<figcaption data-index="1438"><p data-index="1439"><span class="figureLabel" data-index="1440"><b data-index="1441"><a role="doc-backlink" href="#c19-fig-21-1" data-index="1442" data-section-index="29" data-section-idref="c19-fig-21-1" data-target-data-index="1409"><span style=" background-color: #226C7B; color: #FFFFFF;" data-index="1443">ILLUSTRATION 19.21</span></a></b> <b data-index="1444">Computation of Income Tax Expense, 2020</b></span></p></figcaption>
</figure>
<p data-index="1445">The <span class="glossTerm" data-index="1446"><span class="codeColorBlue2" data-index="1447"><b data-index="1448">deferred tax benefit</b></span></span> results from the increase in the deferred tax asset from the beginning to the end of the accounting period (similar to the Chelsea example earlier). The deferred tax benefit is a negative component of income tax expense. The total income tax expense of $90,000 on the income statement for 2020 thus consists of two elements—current tax expense of $100,000 and a deferred tax benefit of $10,000. Hunt makes the following journal entry at the end of 2020 to record income tax expense, deferred income taxes, and income taxes payable.</p>
