<p id="c19-ex-0020" data-index="7565"><span class="codeColorBlue2" data-index="7566"><b data-index="7567">E19.4</b></span> <b class="red" data-index="7568">(LO</b> <a href="c19.xhtml#lo_1" data-index="7569" data-section-index="29" data-section-idref="lo_1" data-target-data-index="87"><b class="red" data-index="7570">1</b></a>, <a href="c19.xhtml#lo_2" data-index="7571" data-section-index="29" data-section-idref="lo_2" data-target-data-index="1838"><b class="red" data-index="7572">2</b></a><span class="red" data-index="7573">)</span> <b data-index="7574">(Three Differences, Compute Taxable Income, Entry for Taxes)</b> Zurich Company reports pretax financial income of $70,000 for 2020. The following items cause taxable income to be different than pretax financial income.</p>
<p class="latin1" data-index="7575"><span class="label" data-index="7576"><b data-index="7577">1.</b>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span> Depreciation on the tax return is greater than depreciation on the income statement by $16,000.</p>
<p class="latin1" data-index="7578"><span class="label" data-index="7579"><b data-index="7580">2.</b>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span> Rent collected on the tax return is greater than rent recognized on the income statement by $22,000.</p>
<p class="latin1" data-index="7581"><span class="label" data-index="7582"><b data-index="7583">3.</b>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span> Fines for pollution appear as an expense of $11,000 on the income statement.</p>
<p data-index="7584">Zurich's tax rate is 30% for all years, and the company expects to report taxable income in all future years. There are no deferred taxes at the beginning of 2020.</p>
